ls xmlns:b="http://schemas.datacontract.org/2004/07/ThreatModelForge.KnowledgeBase"/><a:Behavior i:nil="true"/><a:Description>Native mobile client</a:Description><a:Hidden>false</a:Hidden><a:Id>mobile-app</a:Id><a:ImageLocation>Lower right of stencil</a:ImageLocation><a:ImageSource></a:ImageSource><a:ImageStream i:nil="true"/><a:Name>Mobile App</a:Name><a:ParentId>GE.EI</a:ParentId><a:Representation>Rectangle</a:Representation><a:Shape i:nil="true"/><a:StencilConstraints/></a:ElementType><a:ElementType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Attributes/><a:AvailableToBaseModels xmlns:b="http://schemas.datacontract.org/2004/07/ThreatModelForge.KnowledgeBase"/><a:Behavior i:nil="true"/><a:Description>External API dependency</a:Description><a:Hidden>false</a:Hidden><a:Id>third-party-api</a:Id><a:ImageLocation>Lower right of stencil</a:ImageLocation><a:ImageSource></a:ImageSource><a:ImageStream i:nil="true"/><a:Name>Third-party API</a:Name><a:ParentId>GE.EI</a:ParentId><a:Representation>Rectangle</a:Representation><a:Shape i:nil="true"/><a:StencilConstraints/></a:ElementType></a:StandardElements><a:ThreatCategories><a:ThreatCategory><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Id>S</a:Id><a:LongDescription>Impersonating something or someone else.</a:LongDescription><a:Name>Spoofing</a:Name><a:ShortDescription>Impersonating something or someone else.</a:ShortDescription></a:ThreatCategory><a:ThreatCategory><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Id>T</a:Id><a:LongDescription>Unauthorized modification of data or code.</a:LongDescription><a:Name>Tampering</a:Name><a:ShortDescription>Unauthorized modification of data or code.</a:ShortDescription></a:ThreatCategory><a:ThreatCategory><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Id>R</a:Id><a:LongDescription>Denying an action without other parties being able to prove otherwise.</a:LongDescription><a:Name>Repudiation</a:Name><a:ShortDescription>Denying an action without other parties being able to prove otherwise.</a:ShortDescription></a:ThreatCategory><a:ThreatCategory><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Id>I</a:Id><a:LongDescription>Exposure of information to parties not authorized to see it.</a:LongDescription><a:Name>Information Disclosure</a:Name><a:ShortDescription>Exposure of information to parties not authorized to see it.</a:ShortDescription></a:ThreatCategory><a:ThreatCategory><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Id>D</a:Id><a:LongDescription>Denying or degrading service to legitimate users.</a:LongDescription><a:Name>Denial of Service</a:Name><a:ShortDescription>Denying or degrading service to legitimate users.</a:ShortDescription></a:ThreatCategory><a:ThreatCategory><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Id>E</a:Id><a:LongDescription>Gaining capabilities without proper authorization.</a:LongDescription><a:Name>Elevation of Privilege</a:Name><a:ShortDescription>Gaining capabilities without proper authorization.</a:ShortDescription></a:ThreatCategory></a:ThreatCategories><a:ThreatMetaData i:nil="true"/><a:ThreatTypes><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>I</a:Category><a:Description>Set Cached = No on the flow and read the credential fresh from the store on each use, so a rotated or revoked credential is never served from a stale cache. If a short-lived cache is unavoidable, bound its lifetime to the credential's rotation interval.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1027</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A flow that reads a credential from a store that holds credentials and caches it can serve a stale credential after the credential is rotated or revoked, and the cached copy widens the window during which a leaked credential remains usable (tampering and elevation of privilege via a stale key).

This rule is violated when a flow connected to a credential store (StoresCredentials = Yes) is marked Cached = Yes. It does not fire for flows that read the credential fresh on each use.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>I</a:Category><a:Description>Use an encrypted transport for the flow and update the edge Protocol property accordingly (for example HTTPS instead of HTTP, FTPS or SFTP instead of FTP, LDAPS instead of LDAP, or SSH instead of Telnet). Where possible, require mutual TLS across trust boundaries.

If the edge does not actually cross a trust boundary, correct the placement of the trust boundary or the edge so the diagram reflects reality.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1016</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A data flow that crosses a trust boundary leaves a zone of control, so it is exposed to tampering and information disclosure while in transit. Such flows should use an encrypted transport. When an edge crossing a trust boundary declares a well-known cleartext protocol (for example HTTP, FTP, or Telnet), the data crossing the boundary is unprotected on the wire.

This rule is violated for any edge that crosses a trust boundary and whose Protocol property is a recognized cleartext protocol.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>I</a:Category><a:Description>Keep secrets out of logs: redact or tokenize credentials before they are written, and store secrets in a dedicated secret store rather than the log store. Separate the two responsibilities into distinct elements and correct the StoresLogData or StoresCredentials property so only one applies to each store.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1022</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A data store flagged as recording log data (StoresLogData = Yes) that also stores credentials (StoresCredentials = Yes) is a strong signal that secrets are being written into logs. Logs are typically broadly readable, aggregated, and retained for a long time, so secrets that reach them are exposed to information disclosure far beyond their intended audience.

This rule is violated for any storage element whose StoresLogData and StoresCredentials properties are both Yes.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>D</a:Category><a:Description>Set Backup = Yes on the store once a tested backup and restore path exists, so the credentials or audit trail it holds can be recovered after accidental deletion, corruption, or a destructive attack. Keep at least one backup copy isolated from the primary store so a single compromise cannot destroy both.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1028</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A data store that holds important data but has no backup cannot be recovered if its contents are deleted, corrupted, or destroyed. Loss of a credential store strands the application that depends on those secrets; loss of an audit-log store destroys the evidence needed to prove what happened. Either outcome is a loss of availability, and destroying an audit trail also enables repudiation.

This rule fires when a storage component flagged as holding credentials (StoresCredentials = Yes) or log/audit data (StoresLogData = Yes) has its Backup property set to No or left unset. Stores that are not flagged as holding important data are not reported.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>I</a:Category><a:Description>The rule passes when any of these is true: the edge has a custom attribute of the form "DataType:&lt;value&gt;" (for example "DataType:EUPI"); the edge text states the type as "DataType=&lt;value&gt;" or "DataType:&lt;value&gt;", where the value is one word or several words in parentheses; the edge text mentions one of the configured tags such as EUII or EUPI; the diagram carries a custom attribute "DefaultDataType:&lt;value&gt;"; the diagram has an annotation of the form "DefaultDataType:&lt;value&gt;" or "DefaultDataType=&lt;value&gt;"; or the diagram has an annotation mentioning one of the configured tags such as EUII or Access Control Data.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1013</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>Labelling an edge with the classification of the data it carries is valuable well beyond a privacy review: it tells a reviewer what protections and access controls the data warrants. The rule ships with a known set of classification tags (for example EUII, EUPI, or System Metadata), the list can be tailored at build time, and individual edges may carry their own tags. So the same tag need not be repeated on every edge, the rule also honours a diagram-wide default supplied through an annotation or a custom attribute.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>T</a:Category><a:Description>The rule passes when any of the following holds: the stencil type matches a well-known protocol such as HTTP or HTTPS; the edge has a custom attribute in the "Protocol:&lt;name&gt;" form; the edge text states the protocol as "Protocol:&lt;name&gt;" or "Protocol=&lt;name&gt;"; or the edge text contains the name of a well-known protocol such as HTTP.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1008</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>Every edge should record the protocol it uses so the system is fully described. Threat analysis inspects the protocol to confirm the connection is protected and to surface known input-validation or other weaknesses in that protocol.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>E</a:Category><a:Description>Run the process under a dedicated, low-privilege service account with only the permissions it needs, drop privileges after start-up where possible, and set the process's RunningAs property to that account.

If the process genuinely requires elevated rights, isolate it and minimize what else runs at that privilege level.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1024</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A process should run with the least privilege it needs. A process flagged as running as System or Root/Admin violates least privilege: if it is compromised, the attacker inherits broad control over the host and adjacent resources, turning a single flaw into an elevation of privilege with a large blast radius.

This rule is violated for any process whose RunningAs property is System or Root/Admin.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>I</a:Category><a:Description>Confirm the external party is authorized to receive data of this classification and that a data-sharing agreement or user consent covers it. Minimize what is sent — redact, tokenize, or aggregate the data so no more than necessary leaves the boundary — and encrypt it in transit. If the disclosure is intended and approved, suppress the finding; otherwise reroute or remove the flow.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1030</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>Sensitive data that flows to an external interactor leaves the system's trust and enters a party the model does not control. Once disclosed, the data cannot be recalled, and the receiving party may retain, forward, or expose it beyond the system's intent.

This rule fires when a flow whose DataType is a sensitive classification (EUII, EUPI, Customer Content, Account Data, or Access Control Data) has an external interactor as its destination. Flows carrying non-sensitive or public classifications, and flows between internal components, are not reported. A flow flagged here that represents an intended, authorized disclosure can be suppressed.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>S</a:Category><a:Description>Give each calling principal its own identity instead of one shared, static identity. Set a distinct Identity (and a least-privilege TokenScope) on each caller's flow so the token or certificate issued to one caller cannot be presented by another.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1026</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A single identity that is asserted by flows from two or more distinct sources is a shared, static principal. When several callers present the same identity (the same certificate, token, or subject), the identity's authorization has to cover everything every caller needs, so each caller receives an over-broad token — and a compromise of one caller cannot be distinguished from the others (spoofing and elevation of privilege).

This rule is violated when the same non-empty Identity value is declared on flows that originate from two or more distinct sources. It does not fire for a single principal that reuses its own identity across several of its own flows.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>R</a:Category><a:Description>Route the security-relevant actions of the process to a data store that records audit or log data, and mark that store StoresLogData = Yes. Capture who initiated each action, what was requested, and the outcome, so the actions taken on behalf of a caller can be attributed after the fact. Protect the audit store itself (see the unsigned-audit-log and credentials-in-log rules) so the trail cannot be altered or leaked.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1029</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A process that accepts input from a less trusted zone acts on behalf of callers whose identity and intent it cannot fully trust. If it keeps no durable audit trail, there is no record to attribute those actions to a caller, so a caller can repudiate what they did and an operator cannot reconstruct an incident.

This rule fires when a process receiving a data flow that crosses a trust boundary has no outbound flow to a data store flagged as holding log or audit data (StoresLogData = Yes). Processes that do not receive cross-boundary input, and processes that already write to an audit-log store, are not reported.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>S</a:Category><a:Description>Define an authentication scheme for the process and set its AuthenticationScheme property accordingly (for example mutual TLS, OAuth/OpenID Connect, or a signed API key). Authenticate the caller before performing any privileged operation.

If the inbound flow does not actually cross a trust boundary, correct the placement of the trust boundary or the edge so the diagram reflects reality.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1015</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A process that receives a data flow crossing a trust boundary is an entry point into a more trusted zone and should authenticate its callers. Without authentication, a caller on the other side of the boundary can be impersonated (spoofing) or can reach privileged functionality directly (elevation of privilege).

This rule is violated for any process whose AuthenticationScheme property is None or unset and that has an inbound edge crossing a trust boundary.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>S</a:Category><a:Description>Require the external entity to present a verifiable identity (for example a client certificate, a signed token, or an API key bound to the caller), validate it on the receiving element, and set the external entity's AuthenticatesItself property to Yes.

If the entity does not actually initiate flows into the system, correct the direction of the data flow so the diagram reflects reality.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1023</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>An external entity that initiates a data flow into the system should authenticate itself so the elements it calls can verify who is acting. When it does not authenticate itself (AuthenticatesItself = No or unset), an attacker can spoof its identity and act on its behalf.

This rule is violated for any external interactor whose AuthenticatesItself property is not Yes and that has an outbound data flow to a non-external element.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>I</a:Category><a:Description>Enable encryption at rest for the data store and set its Encrypted property accordingly (for example Yes, At-rest, or TDE). Prefer a managed secret store (such as a key vault) with encryption enabled by default, and ensure backups and snapshots are encrypted as well.

If the store does not actually hold credentials, set StoresCredentials to No so the store is not flagged.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1014</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>Data stores that hold secrets - passwords, API keys, connection strings, tokens, or certificates - should be encrypted at rest. When a component is marked as storing credentials (StoresCredentials = Yes) its Encrypted property should indicate encryption at rest (for example Yes, At-rest, or TDE).

This rule is violated for any storage component whose StoresCredentials property is Yes and whose Encrypted property is No or unset.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>I</a:Category><a:Description>Apply role-based access control (RBAC) or an access control list (ACL) to the store, grant only the identities that need the secrets, and set the store's AccessControl property accordingly.

If the element does not actually hold credentials, correct the StoresCredentials property so the diagram reflects reality.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1020</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A data store flagged as storing credentials (StoresCredentials = Yes) should restrict who can reach it. When its access control is None, Public, or unset, any party that can reach the store can read or tamper with the secrets it holds, leading to information disclosure and elevation of privilege.

This rule is violated for any storage element whose StoresCredentials property is Yes and whose AccessControl property is not RBAC or ACL.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>T</a:Category><a:Description>Validate and sanitize all input the process accepts from across the trust boundary (allow-list validation, parameterized queries, output encoding for downstream sinks), then set its SanitizesInput property to Yes.

If the inbound flow does not actually cross a trust boundary, correct the placement of the trust boundary or the edge so the diagram reflects reality.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1017</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A process that receives a data flow crossing a trust boundary is accepting input from a less trusted zone. If it does not sanitize or validate that input, an attacker can carry injection or tampering payloads (SQL, command, or script injection) into the more trusted zone.

This rule is violated for any process whose SanitizesInput property is No or unset and that has an inbound edge crossing a trust boundary.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>T</a:Category><a:Description>Encode and sanitize output for the sink it is destined for (contextual output encoding for HTML/JS, strict content types, and redaction of sensitive fields), then set the process's SanitizesOutput property to Yes.

If the destination is not actually an external entity, correct the element type or the edge so the diagram reflects reality.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1018</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A process that sends a data flow to an external entity is emitting data into a less trusted zone (for example, a browser or a third-party service). If it does not encode or sanitize that output, attacker-influenced data can be reflected to a client as cross-site scripting or can leak sensitive information (information disclosure).

This rule is violated for any process whose SanitizesOutput property is No or unset and that has an outbound edge to an external interactor.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>R</a:Category><a:Description>Sign or seal log records (for example with an append-only store, a hash chain, or a message authentication code), protect the signing key, and set the store's Signed property to Yes.

If the element does not actually hold log or audit data, correct the StoresLogData property so the diagram reflects reality.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1021</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A data store flagged as holding log or audit data (StoresLogData = Yes) should be signed so that records cannot be altered or deleted without detection. When it is not signed, an attacker can tamper with the log and repudiate the events it is meant to prove.

This rule is violated for any storage element whose StoresLogData property is Yes and whose Signed property is not Yes.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>I</a:Category><a:Description>Set the element's Algorithm (or Cipher) property to an approved authenticated cipher: AES-GCM, AES-CBC+HMAC, or ChaCha20-Poly1305. For the KEK/DEK path, migrate secretbox (XSalsa20-Poly1305) to AES-GCM.

If the value is a placeholder rather than a real cipher, set it to None (or remove the property) so the rule does not apply.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1025</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>An element or flow that declares an encryption algorithm should use a modern, authenticated cipher. Non-authenticated or legacy ciphers (for example secretbox / XSalsa20-Poly1305, AES-CBC without a MAC, 3DES, or RC4) are weaker and, for some organizations, are not compliant (non-FIPS / non-NIST).

This rule is violated for any element or flow whose Algorithm (or Cipher) property names a cipher that is not one of the approved authenticated ciphers: AES-GCM, AES-CBC with HMAC, or ChaCha20-Poly1305. It does not fire when no algorithm is declared.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType><a:ThreatType><a:IsExtension>false</a:IsExtension><a:Category>E</a:Category><a:Description>Run the process with meaningful isolation appropriate to the risk (a dedicated process boundary, a hardened container, or a separate virtual machine) and set its Isolation property accordingly, so a compromise is contained.

If the inbound flow does not actually cross a trust boundary, correct the placement of the trust boundary or the edge so the diagram reflects reality.</a:Description><a:GenerationFilters><a:Exclude/><a:Include/></a:GenerationFilters><a:Id>TM1019</a:Id><a:PropertiesMetaData/><a:RelatedCategory i:nil="true"/><a:ShortTitle>A process that receives a data flow crossing a trust boundary is exposed to a less trusted zone. If it runs with no isolation, a compromise is not contained: the attacker can reach the host, adjacent services, and shared resources, widening the blast radius of the breach (elevation of privilege).

This rule is violated for any process whose Isolation property is None or unset and that has an inbound edge crossing a trust boundary.</a:ShortTitle></a:ThreatType></a:ThreatTypes></KnowledgeBase><Profile><PromptedKb xmlns=""/></Profile></ThreatModel>